          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">How did the Vietnam War end?
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/fall-of-saigon-april-30-1975-vietnam-war-end.png" alt="On April 30, 1975, North Vietnamese troops entered Saigon as the last Americans evacuated the city" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
          <i>On April 30, 1975, North Vietnamese troops entered Saigon as the last Americans evacuated the city. Credits: AP Photo</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">     
         The Vietnam War ended with the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-04-2025-f1-8-fall-of-saigon" target="_blank">fall of Saigon</a> on April 30, 1975, marking the beginning of Vietnam‚Äôs reunification under communist rule. In April 1975, North Vietnamese and Viet Cong forces launched the ‚ÄúSpring Offensive,‚Äù bombarding South Vietnamese defenses and seizing key cities such as Hu·∫ø and ƒê√† N·∫µng. These attacks triggered a massive refugee crisis, with many fleeing the fighting.
        </p>
        
     
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         The rapid North Vietnamese advance, known as the ‚ÄúHo Chi Minh Campaign,‚Äù overwhelmed South Vietnamese troops. President Nguy·ªÖn VƒÉn Thi·ªáu resigned on April 21, blaming the United States for withdrawing support.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         As North Vietnamese tanks approached the gates of the presidential palace, the U.S. initiated <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-04-2025-f1-9-operation-frequent-wind" target="_blank">Operation Frequent Wind</a>, the largest helicopter evacuation in history, rescuing over 7,000 people. Earlier efforts, such as Operations Babylift and New Life, had already evacuated orphans and processed 110,000 refugees.</p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         General D∆∞∆°ng VƒÉn Minh surrendered shortly afterward, effectively dissolving the government of South Vietnam. The fall of Saigon became a powerful symbol of America‚Äôs chaotic and humiliating exit from the war and led to the formal unification of Vietnam under communist leadership. Saigon was later renamed Ho Chi Minh City, and the war's legacy continues to shape the historical and political relationship between the two countries.</p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         The Vietnam War claimed the lives of more than 3 million Vietnamese and 60,000 U.S. soldiers. Even 50 years later, many Vietnamese and American veterans continue to suffer from a wide range of physical and mental health issues.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
